{
  "text": "Structural evolution with irradiation Both types of irradiations, alpha decay self-irradiation (Fig. 2a) or Au ions irradiation (Fig. 2b) , induce a change in the glass structure that has been characterized by the Raman spectroscopy, whose characteristics are qualitatively the same, except for the region above 1250 cm \u22121 where the Raman signal from the Cm-ISG glass, i.e. the B-O stretching band, is covered by the curium luminescence signal. Indeed the first main vibration band at around 490 cm \u22121 , called R band and assigned to the bending and rocking modes of Si-O-Si bonds, [CITATION_1] is shifted to higher wavenumbers with the irradiation dose. It corresponds to a decrease of the mean angle in between the silica tetrahedra.",
